Here is an example of how to create a chessboard in LaTeX using FEN notation:

\begin{code}
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}
\begin{center}
\scalebox{0.5}{\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
  \foreach \x in {0,...,\xmax}{%
    \foreach \y in {0,...,\ymax}{%
      \fill[gray!20!white] (\x,\y) -- (\x,\y+1) -- (\x+1,\y+1) -- (\x+1,\y) -- cycle;%
    }%
  }%
  \draw[very thick] (0,0) grid[step=1cm] (\xmax, \ymax);%
  \node at (45:1) {\tiny FEN: %
    rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR};%
\end{tikzpicture}}
\end{center}
\end{document}
\end{code}

The FEN notation in the middle of the document shows a sample position with all the necessary information to render the board in a chess program. The `\foreach` loops through the rows and columns, filling in the squares with gray and drawing a grid line with thick lines. The `\node` adds the FEN notation at the center of the board. The output will look like this:
